<subSubSection lastPageId="29" lastPageNumber="28" pageId="28" pageNumber="27" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="28.[192,1440,1634,1722]" pageId="28" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,302,1634,1658]" pageId="28" pageNumber="27">Ecology</emphasis>
. Lowland, montane. Epigean. Banks and beds of rivers and brooks, close to the water. Open ground; wet, sandy bare soil with scattered stones. Nocturnal; hides during the day among gravel and under stones. Gregarious.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[192,1441,1761,1850]" pageId="28" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,297,1761,1785]" pageId="28" pageNumber="27">Biology</emphasis>
. Seasonality: September–May. Tenerals: November–December, March. Occasionally infested with fungi (Laboulbeniales). Once observed with pseudoscorpion attached to body (TO). Defence mechanism: when alarmed, the adult escapes by running.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[192,1440,193,250]" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,419,193,218]" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">Dispersal power</emphasis>
. Macropterous, probably capable of flight. Fast runner. Vagility likely favoured by flight capacity.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[192,896,289,314]" box="[192,896,289,314]" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,493,289,313]" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">Collecting techniques</emphasis>
. Raking the soil; turning stones.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[192,1440,353,410]" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">
